Follow Anjunadeep on Spotify: http://po.st/sAnjunadeep

Hailing from Brooklyn, NY, Peter Dougherty aka Moon Boots has left his cosmic footprint on the underground electronic scene over recent years, breaking through as a founding member of the influential French Express collective, before earning tastemaker plaudits for his remixes of Robyn, CHVRCHES and George Maple. Over the past 2 years he has taken his sound global with a busy touring schedule taking in some of the world’s best clubs and music festivals.

Moon Boots made his Anjunadeep debut in late 2015 with ‘Red Sky’, a cult favourite with support from Annie Mac, Skream, Jason Bentley, Jamie Jones, Gorgon City, and more. He returns to the label with ‘Tear My Heart’ feat. Lulu James, the first single to be taken from his forthcoming debut album First Landing, set for release on Anjunadeep this year. He follows in the footsteps of Dusky, Lane 8 and Cubicolor in releasing a debut LP on the acclaimed London based imprint.

Fusing Pete's love of classic US house sounds with Lulu’s soulful flair, ‘Tear My Heart’ is full of warm low-end and textured melodies beneath Lulu’s bright, passionate vocals. Label boss James Grant returns to the Deep Edition this week with a special 2 and a half hour mix.

"I was in Deep 08 hibernation mode for most of the second half of last year so this is my first Deep Edition since the summer. During that time I've been quietly stockpiling tunes and probably feeling a bit frustrated not to have an outlet for them :). So this is an extended mix featuring many of those tracks, plus a sprinkling of new bits as well."

Following his Anjunadeep debut last year with 'Seven Summits EP', Matthias Vogt's distinct brand of intricate and emotive electronica has continued to turn heads, warranting support from industry tastemakers including Pete Tong, John Digweed, Dixon and Dusky to name a few. Hot off the heels of his latest single 'Matters', Vogt returns with another electronic gem 'Higher Love' featuring the smooth vocals of Swedish soul singer Jonatan Bäckelie. The package also features two deep house reworks from talented All Day I Dream affiliate Powel, a pair of textured dance-floor minded moments.

Release Date: 8th July 2016

Since their Anjunadeep debut in 2014 with ‘You Would / Mad Dog’, Thomas Schwartz & Fausto Fanizza have delivered a steady stream of consistent and quality club ready cuts including the notable ‘Kirk’, ‘Circles’ and most recently ‘Dawn To Dusk’, a definitive highlight from last years iTunes dance #1 album 'Anjunadeep 07’.

As well as becoming firm favourites with the Anjuna fanbase, the Italian duo's distinctive brand of uplifting and emotive house has won them support from industry tastemakers such as BBC Radio 1’s Annie Mac. Returning with their most extensive release to date, Schwartz & Fanizza deliver 4 classy productions in the form of the ‘Rea EP’.

Opening the package the first of two collaborations with vocalist Susie Ledge, ‘Secret Place’ fuses surging low-end with cascading melodies and wistful lyrics. Next up in rolling balearic style is ‘Voices’ featuring trademark Schwartz & Fanizza chords. ‘I Can’t Be Found’ also features Susie Ledge’s delicate vocals, above an evocative xylophone riff and atmospheric bass grooves. Rounding off the Ep, title track ‘Rea’ is a prime example of their warm sound, packed with harmonic depth and soulful flair, blending chopped vocal samples and shuffling percussion.

Frenchman Jeremy Villecourt aka Croquet Club has become an Anjunadeep fan favourite over the past two years with his unique brand of delicate downtempo electronica. With support from international tastemakers like Zane Lowe, Jason Bentley and Rob Da Bank under his belt, and coverage from The Line Of Best Fit, Mixmag and Indie Shuffle, Croquet Club now returns with his most expansive project to date – ‘Love Exposure’.

Following in the footsteps of legendary French acts like Air, Sebastian Tellier and Etienne De Crecy (who featured Croquet Club’s ‘Jacuzzi’ in his latest BBC Essential Mix), the six track mini-album sees Jeremy showcase his quirky style in true gallic fashion.

The blissful beatlessness of ‘Andante’ ushers us into Villecourt’s musical world, before his own vocals appear in the soulful ‘Careless Love’. ‘Summer’ is a joyous slice of dancefloor fun, melodic basslines bouncing beneath wistful vocals.

‘Go Slow’ will be familiar to Anjunadeep regulars after it’s appearance on the iTunes #1 Dance album ‘Anjunadeep 07’ recently – an intricate fusion of soft piano and rolling groove. Jeremy’s vocals take centre stage in 'Eternité' where his breathy lyrics, sung in French, loop hypnotically above bubbling atmospherics, before ‘You Left Me’ ends things on a beautifully contemplative note.

Release Date: 17th June 2016

Frenchman Jeremy Villecourt aka Croquet Club has become an Anjunadeep fan favourite over the past two years with his unique brand of delicate downtempo electronica. With support from international tastemakers like Zane Lowe, Jason Bentley and Rob Da Bank under his belt, and coverage from The Line Of Best Fit, Mixmag and Indie Shuffle, Croquet Club now returns with his most expansive project to date – ‘Love Exposure’.

Following in the footsteps of legendary French acts like Air, Sebastian Tellier and Etienne De Crecy (who featured Croquet Club’s ‘Jacuzzi’ in his latest BBC Essential Mix), the six track mini-album sees Jeremy showcase his quirky style in true gallic fashion.

The blissful beatlessness of ‘Andante’ ushers us into Villecourt’s musical world, before his own vocals appear in the soulful ‘Careless Love’. ‘Summer’ is a joyous slice of dancefloor fun, melodic basslines bouncing beneath wistful vocals.

‘Go Slow’ will be familiar to Anjunadeep regulars after it’s appearance on the iTunes #1 Dance album ‘Anjunadeep 07’ recently – an intricate fusion of soft piano and rolling groove. Jeremy’s vocals take centre stage in 'Eternité' where his breathy lyrics, sung in French, loop hypnotically above bubbling atmospherics, before ‘You Left Me’ ends things on a beautifully contemplative note.

Release Date: 27th May 2016

2015 was a seminal year for Joe Ashworth, with the release of his debut artist album ‘Grain’ on respected London imprint Needwant. Earning widespread support from leading tastemakers John Digweed, Anja Schneider, George Fitzgerald, Jonas Rathsman, B. Traits, Mano Le Tough and Detroit Swindle, as well as acclaim from the likes of DJMag, making it into their coveted Top 20 album list of 2015.

Croquet Club announces ‘Love Exposure’ mini-album coming this summer on Anjunadeep. First single ‘Careless Love’ available now as an instant grat download on iTunes, and to stream on all platforms.

Frenchman Jeremy Villecourt aka Croquet Club has become an Anjunadeep fan favourite over the past two years with his unique brand of delicate downtempo electronica. With support from international tastemakers like Zane Lowe, Jason Bentley and Rob Da Bank under his belt, and coverage from The Line Of Best Fit, Mixmag and Indie Shuffle, Croquet Club now returns with his most expansive project to date – ‘Love Exposure’.

Following in the footsteps of legendary French acts like Air, Sebastian Tellier and Etienne De Crecy (who featured Croquet Club’s ‘Jacuzzi’ in his latest BBC Essential Mix), the six track mini-album sees Jeremy showcase his quirky style in true gallic fashion.

The blissful beatlessness of ‘Andante’ ushers us into Villecourt’s musical world, before his own vocals appear in the soulful ‘Careless Love’. ‘Summer’ is a joyous slice of dancefloor fun, melodic basslines bouncing beneath wistful vocals.

‘Go Slow’ will be familiar to Anjunadeep regulars after it’s appearance on the iTunes #1 Dance album ‘Anjunadeep 07’ recently – an intricate fusion of soft piano and rolling groove. Jeremy’s vocals take centre stage in Eternité where his breathy lyrics, sung in French, loop hypnotically above bubbling atmospherics, before ‘You Left Me’ ends things on a beautifully contemplative note.

A highlight from the iTunes #1 compilation ‘Anjunadeep 07’, Ryan Davis’ melancholic beauty ‘Brun’ gets reworked by two leading lights of the European underground, Luca Bacchetti and Matthias Meyer. Over the past decade Ryan Davis has carved out his own niche, with a unique brand of melodic techno, attracting wide-spread support from the likes of Hernan Cattaneo, Sasha, Jonas Rathsman, Stephan Bodzin and Max Cooper.

Frenchman Jeremy Villecourt aka Croquet Club has become an Anjunadeep fan favourite over the past two years with his unique brand of delicate downtempo electronica. With support from international tastemakers like Zane Lowe, Jason Bentley and Rob Da Bank under his belt, and coverage from The Line Of Best Fit, Mixmag and Indie Shuffle, Croquet Club now returns with his most expansive project to date – ‘Love Exposure’.

Following in the footsteps of legendary French acts like Air, Sebastian Tellier and Etienne De Crecy (who featured Croquet Club’s ‘Jacuzzi’ in his latest BBC Essential Mix), the six track mini-album sees Jeremy showcase his quirky style in true gallic fashion.

The blissful beatlessness of ‘Andante’ ushers us into Villecourt’s musical world, before his own vocals appear in the soulful ‘Careless Love’. ‘Summer’ is a joyous slice of dancefloor fun, melodic basslines bouncing beneath wistful vocals.

‘Go Slow’ will be familiar to Anjunadeep regulars after it’s appearance on the iTunes #1 Dance album ‘Anjunadeep 07’ recently – an intricate fusion of soft piano and rolling groove. Jeremy’s vocals take centre stage in 'Eternité' where his breathy lyrics, sung in French, loop hypnotically above bubbling atmospherics, before ‘You Left Me’ ends things on a beautifully contemplative note.

Berlin’s Ryan Davis has carved out a niche all of his own over the past 10 years, releasing exquisite melodic techno and electronica on revered labels Bedrock, Traum, and his own Klangwelt label. Along the way he’s been championed by Sasha, Stephan Bodzin, Hernan Cattaneo and John Digweed, and collaborated with Max Cooper and Applescal. The ‘From Within EP’ marks his first original release on Anjunadeep following memorable remixes of Andrew Bayer and Olafur Arnalds.

The cinematic ‘Paper Rockets’ begins the EP in subtle fashion, showcasing Ryan’s talent for intricate production and mellow moods. ‘Brun’ a stand-out from last year’s ‘Anjunadeep 07’ compilation has the hallmarks of an Anjunadeep classic, combining club-ready sounds with emotional melodies that tug at the heart-strings.

Selling out shows from LA to London, Daniel Goldstein aka Lane 8 marked himself out as one of electronic music’s rising stars in 2015 with the release of his acclaimed debut album ‘Rise’ on Anjunadeep. Highly praised by The New York Times, Hype Machine, Mixmag, The Fader and The Metro, and supported by global tastemakers Annie Mac, Jason Bentley and Pete Tong, Lane 8’s diverse sound connected with audiences across the board.

Casting new light on the songs and musicality at its heart, ‘Rise (Live & In Session)’ collates live and session recordings of five tracks from the album, recorded with collaborators Solomon Grey and Lulu James and featuring live keys and arrangement from Daniel himself.

Album opener ‘Loving You’ appears as an ‘In Session’ performance with original vocalist and Jon Hopkins collaborator Lulu James.

Long-time collaborators Solomon Grey return on of ‘Diamonds’ and ‘Hot As You Want’, taken from the popular ‘In Session’ videos debuted last year, originally premiered by Fact Magazine.

With the release of his debut artist album ‘Rise’ on Anjunadeep last summer Lane 8 aka Daniel Goldstein established himself as one of the electronic scene’s most exciting talents, warranting a stream of support from international tastemakers including Pete Tong, Jason Bentley and Annie Mac along with glowing coverage from The New York Times, Mixmag and The Fader. 

Lane 8 follows with a collection of high calibre remixes from a host of talented producers, along with new mixes from Anjunadeep stalwart Jody Wisternoff, emerging British talent Theo Kottis, as well as his own rework of album opener ‘Loving You’.

Lane 8’s rework of 'Loving You’ twists the vocal finesse of Lulu James into a brooding tech-house roller that explores the darker side of Goldstein’s production; an undeniable dance floor weapon. Fresh off the heels of his Anjunadeep debut ‘Into The Wild’, Theo Kottis takes to the stage again with an atmospheric down-tempo remix of melodic gem ‘Klara’.

Jody Wisternoff offers a hallmark uplifting remix of vocal track ‘Sunlight’. Wisternoff layers a punchy bassline groove with mellow synths beneath the summery topline. Further remixes come from some of the scenes most in demand names, including Audion (aka Matthew Dear), Moon Boots, Kiwi, Yotto and Bwana.

Berlin’s Martin Roth returns with ‘Have You Ever’, a highlight from 2015’s iTunes Dance #1 album ‘Anjunadeep 07’.

A fan favourite with label classics like ‘Beautiful Life’ and ‘Deep Style’ in his discography, Roth show’s off his playful side in ‘Have You Ever’, his first original release since 2014’s ‘Mel / Maya’. An off-beat groove paired with inventive percussion drives beneath soaring pads and steel drum chimes to great effect, but it’s the DJ Koze-esque stuttering vocal sample that steals the show in this unique melodic gem.

Two UK talents now step up for remix duties – Medlar and Kahwe.

Medlar has previously remixed Disclosure, Groove Armada and Tensnake, and put out a string of gorgeous EPs on Wolf Music. He ups the ante on his remix, blending the original melodies with dark bassline and punchy percussion.

Kahwe brings his own unique style to proceedings, delivering a mellow take full of atmospheric live percussion, warm fuzzy basslines and cascading melodies. Over the course of their 20-year partnership as Way Out West, Nick Warren and Jody Wisternoff have amassed an enviable array of achievements. 

From reaching the top 20 in the UK singles chart and bringing their infamous live show to Glastonbury, to their acclaimed remixes for UNKLE, James Holden and BT, and now their respective solo careers as globe-trotting DJs. 

Seven years after their last album Warren and Wisternoff reunite for the their 5th LP, slated for release on Anjunadeep in 2016. The first piece of music to be debuted from the album is the stunning “Tuesday Maybe” first heard on the recent iTunes Dance #1 ‘Anjunadeep 07’ compilation. 

Haunting strings flow beneath mysterious vocals as subtle melodic textures ebb and flow around a hypnotic groove in this multi-layered beauty.

Release Date: 12th February 2016

Hailing from Montreal via New York, Gab Rhome is part of a new wave of underground producers from North America, whose deft melodic house has won him support from Lee Burridge, Sasha, Guy Gerber and Henry Saiz, along with releases on their respective labels.

He returns to Anjunadeep following 2015’s ‘Drifting EP’ with another fine selection of underground house cuts. Title track ‘Ceremonie Des Adieux’ showcases Gab’s flair for mystic atmospheres and exotic instrumentation, with chord stabs rising and falling beneath intricate strings.

‘Cashmere’ is pure peak-time action, fusing chugging tech-house grooves with a quirky and instantly catchy riff, along with spacey vocal samples. ‘The Spice Trade’ is a mellow journey through Middle Eastern sounds and unorthodox samples. Rising French talent The Mekanism closes out the EP with his energetic take on The Spice Trade, twisting it into a club-ready roller.
